<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITY HALL ROUNDUP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 BEVERLY HILLS: City officials have complained to neighboring West Hollywood 
that its proposed zoning plan, which could add 1.1 million square feet of 
development to the Sunset Strip, does not take into account the effect on 
Beverly Hills. 
</P>
<P>
 In a 15-page letter to West Hollywood, Beverly Hills officials cited such 
worries as increased traffic and parking. 
</P>
<P>
 The letter is expected to be just part of a long-term debate among West 
Hollywood, its residents and neighboring cities regarding the proposal that 
would address development along 1.2 miles of Sunset Boulevard. 
</P>
<P>
 CULVER CITY: The City Council met in a closed session on Monday to discuss 
communication issues with Culver City Police Chief Ted Cooke. The meeting was 
billed on the council's agenda as Cooke's performance evaluation, although it 
was scheduled two weeks ago after a group of angry Culver City residents 
protested the hiring of Timothy Wind as a community service officer. 
</P>
<P>
 Wind, a former Los Angeles police officer, was acquitted of state and federal 
charges stemming from the beating of Rodney G. King. Residents complained that 
hiring Wind made the city appear insensitive to the issues surrounding King's 
beating and the 1992 riots after the acquittal in state court of Wind and three 
other officers. 
</P>
<P>
 The council has not released information about the closed session, but the 
city is expected to make public a memo prepared by the city's Chief 
Administrative Office explaining Cooke's rationale for hiring Wind. 
</P>
<P>
 MEETINGS NEXT WEEK * Beverly Hills: 7:30 p.m. Wednesday, 450 Crescent Drive, 
(310) 285-2400. 
</P>
<P>
 * Culver City: 7 p.m. Monday, Interim City Hall, Trailer No. 1, 4095 Overland 
Ave., (310) 202-5851. 
</P>
<P>
 * Los Angeles: 10 a.m. Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday, 200 N. Spring St., (213) 
485-3126. 
</P>
<P>
 * Malibu: 6:30 p.m. Monday, Hughes Laboratory, 3011 Malibu Canyon Rd., (310) 
456-2489. 
</P>
<P>
 * West Hollywood: 7 p.m. Monday, West Hollywood Park gymnasium, 647 N. San 
Vicente Blvd., (310) 854-7400. 
