<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: SAN ONOFRE; SURFER, 39, PULLED OUT OF OCEAN DIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF BEAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 39-year-old Cardiff man died Tuesday after he paddled out on a surfboard to 
take advantage of larger-than-normal waves generated by tropical storm Olivia. 
</P>
<P>
 The victim, identified Wednesday as Marc Woods, was pulled from the ocean 
about 9:50 a.m. after another surfer discovered him face down in the 
water.Woods was taken to Samaritan Medical Center-San Clemente, where he was 
pronounced dead at 11:16 a.m., said a spokeswoman for the Orange County 
coroner's office. 
</P>
<P>
 An autopsy has been completed, the spokeswoman said, but the official cause of 
death will not be released pending results from toxicology and microscopic 
tissue tests. Woods had no history of medical problems, she said. 
</P>
<P>
 Mike Tope, chief ranger at San Onofre State Beach, said the surfer who found 
Woods had exchanged pleasantries with him a few moments earlier while both were 
paddling out in an area about 150 yards from shore where the waves don't break. 
The area is between two surfing spots known as "Old Man's" and "The Point." 
</P>
<P>
 Tope said the witness reported that Woods' hair was dry and he was wearing a 
full wet suit when the two men spoke. But Woods was gasping and unconscious 
when the surfer next found him, Tope said. The man and two other surfers 
brought Woods to the beach, where two other bystanders helped begin CPR, Tope 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Woods was one of several surfers lured to the water Tuesday by 
larger-than-normal surf, Tope said. The waves were smaller Wednesday, and no 
other serious incidents were reported. 
</P>
<P>
 The coroner's spokeswoman said that Woods lived in a motor home and kept a 
post office box in Cardiff-by-the-Sea. 
</P>
<P>
 Woods, who worked for a fire extinguisher company in San Diego County, was 
unmarried and had no children, the spokeswoman said.JEFF BEAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
